## 14. Key Design Decisions

### Why Redis Streams instead of Message Brokers (RabbitMQ/Kafka)?

Redis Streams provides sufficient consumer group semantics for current scale, avoiding additional infrastructure dependencies while enabling crash recovery via XPENDING/XCLAIM. Dual-stream priority mechanism (contest vs normal) would be more complex in traditional message brokers.

### Why Standalone Judge Worker instead of In-process Judging?

Sandboxed execution requires Linux-specific capabilities (cgroups, seccomp, chroot) and syscall-level process control that's unstable when mixed with HTTP server. Decoupling workers allows independent scaling (more workers = more concurrent judging) and horizontal deployment across machines. Worker crashes don't affect API service.

### Why JWT-based Tenant Identity instead of Request Headers?

Storing `school_id` in signed JWT prevents client forgery of organization identity. `tenant_middleware` explicitly ignores any `X-Tenant-ID` request headers, reading only from JWT Claims injected by `auth_middleware`. This makes tenant isolation tamper-proof at transport layer.

### Why One Crate Per Domain instead of Monolithic API Crate?

Each domain crate has its own `routes.rs`, `models.rs`, and `service.rs`, making codebase more navigable and testable. Domain crates depend on `api-infra` and `shared` but not on each other, preventing circular dependencies. New domains can be added as independent workspace members.

### Why In-memory RBAC Matrix instead of Database-driven Permissions?

Role-permission mapping is static and changes infrequently. In-memory `HashSet` lookups are orders of magnitude faster than per-request database queries. Matrix defined in `api-infra/src/rbac.rs` can be migrated to database model in future without changing permission check API.

### Why Single Shared `reqwest::Client` for Workers?

Creating new HTTP clients per request loses TCP keep-alive and requires new TLS handshake. Single shared `reqwest::Client` maintains internal connection pool, reducing latency for result callbacks to API.

### Why Standalone Feature Gateway Service?

- **Decoupling**: Feature flag resolution doesn't impact API service performance
- **Independent Scaling**: Gateway can scale based on flag check volume
- **Direct Database Access**: No dependency on API service for database queries
- **Emergency-off**: System-wide feature disable via single env var without touching API
- **Scoped Hierarchy**: Complex precedence (class > grade > campus > global > default) centralized

